{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17641501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17641501"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:27:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:27:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17881"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17881"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.26,0,0.05,0.32,0.37]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10595"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115097"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10595"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17881"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97105"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10053"},{"type":"tags","id":"10062"},{"type":"tags","id":"10068"},{"type":"tags","id":"11228"},{"type":"tags","id":"11248"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24696"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24699"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115097"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about metabolic changes during fasting is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acetyl-CoA is used to produce ketone bodies","Muscle protein is the first source of energy during fasting","Red blood cells switch to using ketone bodies","Fatty acids are converted to glucose for energy","Glycogen stores are the primary energy source after 24 hours of fasting"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring fasting, the body undergoes several metabolic changes to maintain energy supply. \u003Cstrong\u003EAcetyl-CoA is used to produce ketone bodies\u003C/strong\u003E, which serve as an alternative energy source for the brain and other tissues when glucose is scarce. Fatty acids released from adipose tissue are converted to acetyl-CoA, but acetyl-CoA cannot be converted into glucose. Instead, it enters the citric acid cycle or is used for ketone body production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFatty acids are converted to glucose for energy\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because fatty acids are broken down into acetyl-CoA, which cannot be converted into glucose. Instead, they are used for energy production or ketone body synthesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERed blood cells switch to using ketone bodies\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because red blood cells lack mitochondria and rely solely on glucose for energy, even during fasting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlycogen stores are the primary energy source after 24 hours of fasting\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because glycogen stores are typically depleted within 24 hours of fasting, after which the body relies on gluconeogenesis and ketone bodies for energy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle protein is the first source of energy during fasting\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because the body initially uses glycogen stores and then shifts to fatty acid oxidation and ketone body production before significantly breaking down muscle protein.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["During fasting, fatty acids are released from adipose tissue and converted to acetyl-CoA, which provides energy for most tissues.","Acetyl-CoA cannot be converted into glucose; it enters the citric acid cycle or is used for ketone body production.","Red blood cells rely solely on glucose for energy, even during fasting, as they lack mitochondria."],"references":["Bender DA, Cunningham SM. Introduction to nutrition and metabolism. Boca Raton: CRC Press; 2021.","Salway JG. Metabolism at a Glance. 4th ed. Chichester: John Wiley \u0026 Sons; 2016.","Chandel NS. Amino Acid Metabolism. Cold Spring Harb Perspect Biol. 2021 Apr 1;13(4):a040584.","Ling ZN, Jiang YF, Ru JN, Lu JH, Ding B, Wu J. Amino acid metabolism in health and disease. Signal Transduct Target Ther. 2023 Sep 13;8(1):345."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97105"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17881"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97105","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97105"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-22T11:17:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-22T11:17:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10595"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115097"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"descri